04985nam a22006975i 9780813554808DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2007    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135548087 a10.36019/97808135548082doi  a(DE-B1597)526273  a(OCoLC)476126531  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREF0000002bisacsh1 aGargiullo, Margaret B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.12aA Guide to Native Plants of the New York City Region /cMargaret B. Gargiullo. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (338 p.) :b131  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tKeys to Plant Characteristics -- tPart I. Plants of New York City and Vicinity -- tChapter 1. Trees -- tChapter 2. Shrubs -- tChapter 3. Vines -- tChapter 4. Herbs -- tChapter 5. Graminoids -- tChapter 6. Ferns -- tPart II. Plants for Various Habitat Types -- tChapter 7. Plants for Open Habitats, Full Sun -- tChapter 8. Plants for Forest Restorations -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is no secret that with each new office park, strip mall, and housing development that slices through the New York, New Jersey, and Connecticut landscape, more and more indigenous plant habitats are being destroyed. Concrete, after all, is not a friendly neighbor to vegetative life. Less common wisdom, however, holds that plants native to this region have been disappearing rapidly for a variety of reasons, and some of the causes can be avoided, even as construction projects continue to move in. One of the most serious threats to indigenous plants is the introduction of invasive non-native species by landscapers after new developments are built. In this unique guide, ecologist Margaret B. Gargiullo presents a detailed look at the full scope of flora that is native to this region and available for propagation. Geared specifically for landscape architects, designers, land managers, and restorationists, this book offers practical advice on how to increase the amount of indigenous flora growing in the mepolitan area, and in some cases, to reintroduce plants that have completely disappeared. More than one hundred line drawings of plants and their specific habitats, ranging from forests to beaches, help readers visualize the full potential for landscaping in the area. A separate entry for each plant also provides detailed information on size, flower color, blooming time, and its possible uses in wetland mitigation, erosion control, and natural area restoration. Some plants are also highlighted for their ability to thrive in areas that are typically considered inhospitable to greenery. Easily searchable by plant type or habitat, this guide is an essential reference for everyone concerned with the region's natural plant life. Since most of the plants can also be grown well beyond the New York City metropolitan area, this book will also be useful for project managers doing restoration work in most of southern New England and the mid-Atlantic region, including Pennsylvania, Delaware, and Maryland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aREFERENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813554808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813554808.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 20